   HHOOLLIIDDAAYYSS
       Holidays  are  entered  either  directly  in the .taskrc file or via an include file that is specified in .taskrc. For single-day holidays the name and the date is required to be
       given:

                     holiday.towel.name=Day of the towel
                     holiday.towel.date=20100525

       For holidays that span a range of days (i.e. vacation), you can use a start date and an end date:

                     holiday.sysadmin.name=System Administrator Appreciation Week
                     holiday.sysadmin.start=20100730
                     holiday.sysadmin.end=20100805

              Dates are to be entered according to the setting in the dateformat.holiday variable.

              The following holidays are computed automatically: Good Friday (goodfriday), Easter (easter), Easter Monday (eastermonday), Ascension (ascension),  Pentecost  (pentecost).
              The date for these holidays is the given keyword:

                     holiday.eastersunday.name=Easter
                     holiday.eastersunday.date=easter

       Note that the Taskwarrior distribution contains example holiday files that can be included like this:

                     include holidays.en-US.rc

   DDEEPPEENNDDEENNCCIIEESS
       ddeeppeennddeennccyy..rreemmiinnddeerr==11
              Determines whether dependency chain violations generate reminders.

       ddeeppeennddeennccyy..ccoonnffiirrmmaattiioonn==11
              Determines whether dependency chain repair requires confirmation.

   CCOOLLOORR CCOONNTTRROOLLSS
       ccoolloorr==11
              May be "1" or "0". Determines whether Taskwarrior uses color. When "0", will use dashes (-----) to underline column headings.

       ffoonnttuunnddeerrlliinnee==11
              Determines if font underlines or ASCII dashes should be used to underline headers, even when color is enabled.

       Taskwarrior  has a number of coloration rules. They correspond to a particular attribute of a task, such as it being due, or being active, and specifies the automatic coloring of
       that task. A list of valid colors, depending on your terminal, can be obtained by running the command:

              ttaasskk ccoolloorrss

              Note that no default values are listed here - the defaults now correspond to the dark-256.theme (Linux) and dark-16.theme (other) theme values.  The coloration  rules  are
              as follows:

              ccoolloorr..dduuee..ttooddaayy Task is due today
              ccoolloorr..aaccttiivvee Task is started, therefore active.
              ccoolloorr..sscchheedduulleedd Task is scheduled, therefore ready for work.
              ccoolloorr..uunnttiill Task has an expiration date.
              ccoolloorr..bblloocckkiinngg Task is blocking another in a dependency.
              ccoolloorr..bblloocckkeedd Task is blocked by a dependency.
              ccoolloorr..oovveerrdduuee Task is overdue (due some time prior to now).
              ccoolloorr..dduuee Task is coming due.
              ccoolloorr..pprroojjeecctt..nnoonnee Task does not have an assigned project.
              ccoolloorr..ttaagg..nnoonnee Task has no tags.
              ccoolloorr..ttaaggggeedd Task has at least one tag.
              ccoolloorr..rreeccuurrrriinngg Task is recurring.
              ccoolloorr..ccoommpplleetteedd Task is completed.
              ccoolloorr..ddeelleetteedd Task is deleted.

              To disable a coloration rule for which there is a default, set the value to nothing, for example:
                     ccoolloorr..ttaaggggeedd==

              By  default, colors produced by rules blend. This has the advantage of conveying additional information, by producing combinations that are not used by any particular rule
              directly.

              However, color blending can produce highlighting combinations which are not desired. In such cases, use the following option to disable this behaviour:

       rruullee..ccoolloorr..mmeerrggee==11
              Can be "1" or "0". When "0", disables merging of colors produced by different color rules. Use if your color scheme produces unpleasing foreground and background  combina‐
              tions.

              See the task-color(5) man pages for color details.

       Certain attributes like tags, projects and keywords can have their own coloration rules.

