   UURRGGEENNCCYY
       The urgency calculation uses a polynomial with several terms, each of which has a configurable coefficient. Those coefficients are:

       uurrggeennccyy..bblloocckkiinngg..ccooeeffffiicciieenntt==88..00
              Urgency coefficient for blocking tasks
       uurrggeennccyy..bblloocckkeedd..ccooeeffffiicciieenntt==--55..00
              Urgency coefficient for blocked tasks
       uurrggeennccyy..dduuee..ccooeeffffiicciieenntt==1122..00
              Urgency coefficient for due dates
       uurrggeennccyy..wwaaiittiinngg..ccooeeffffiicciieenntt==--33..00
              Urgency coefficient for waiting status
       uurrggeennccyy..aaccttiivvee..ccooeeffffiicciieenntt==44..00
              Urgency coefficient for active tasks
       uurrggeennccyy..sscchheedduulleedd..ccooeeffffiicciieenntt==55..00
              Urgency coefficient for scheduled tasks
       uurrggeennccyy..pprroojjeecctt..ccooeeffffiicciieenntt==11..00
              Urgency coefficient for projects
       uurrggeennccyy..ttaaggss..ccooeeffffiicciieenntt==11..00
              Urgency coefficient for tags
       uurrggeennccyy..aannnnoottaattiioonnss..ccooeeffffiicciieenntt==11..00
              Urgency coefficient for annotations
       uurrggeennccyy..aaggee..ccooeeffffiicciieenntt==22..00
              Urgency coefficient for the age of tasks
       uurrggeennccyy..aaggee..mmaaxx==336655
              Maximum age in days. After this number of days has elapsed, the urgency of a task won't increase any more because of aging.
       uurrggeennccyy..uusseerr..ttaagg..<<ttaagg>>..ccooeeffffiicciieenntt==......
              Specific tag coefficient.
       uurrggeennccyy..uusseerr..ttaagg..nneexxtt..ccooeeffffiicciieenntt==1155..00
              Urgency coefficient for tag 'next'.
       uurrggeennccyy..uusseerr..pprroojjeecctt..<<pprroojjeecctt>>..ccooeeffffiicciieenntt==......
              Specific project coefficient.
       uurrggeennccyy..uusseerr..kkeeyywwoorrdd..<<kkeeyywwoorrdd>>..ccooeeffffiicciieenntt==......
              Specific description keyword coefficient.
       uurrggeennccyy..uuddaa..<<nnaammee>>..ccooeeffffiicciieenntt==......
              Presence/absence of UDA data.
       uurrggeennccyy..uuddaa..<<nnaammee>>..<<vvaalluuee>>..ccooeeffffiicciieenntt==......
              Specific value of UDA data.

       The  coefficients  reflect the relative importance of the various terms in the urgency calculation. These are default values, and may be modified to suit your preferences, but it
       is important that you carefully consider any modifications.

       uurrggeennccyy..iinnhheerriitt==00
              Not actually a coefficient. When enabled, blocking tasks inherit the highest urgency value found in the tasks they block. This is done recursively.  It is  recommended  to
              set urgency.blocking.coefficient and urgency.blocked.coefficient to 0.0 in order for this setting to be the most useful.

   DDEEFFAAUULLTTSS
       ddeeffaauulltt..pprroojjeecctt==ffoooo
              Provides a default project name for the _t_a_s_k _a_d_d command, if you don't specify one. The default is blank.

       ddeeffaauulltt..dduuee==......
              Provides  a  default due date for the _t_a_s_k _a_d_d command, if you don't specify one. You can use a date, or a duration value which is assumed to be relative to 'now'. The de‐
              fault is blank.

       ddeeffaauulltt..sscchheedduulleedd==......
              Provides a default scheduled date for the _t_a_s_k _a_d_d command, if you don't specify one. You can use a date, or a duration value which is assumed to be relative to 'now'. The
              default is blank.

       uuddaa..<<nnaammee>>..ddeeffaauulltt==......
              Provides default values for UDA fields when using the _t_a_s_k _a_d_d command, if you don't specify values. The default is blank.

       ddeeffaauulltt..ccoommmmaanndd==nneexxtt
              Provides a default command that is run every time Taskwarrior is invoked with no arguments. For example, if set to:

                     default.command=project:foo list

              then Taskwarrior will run the "project:foo list" command if no command is specified. This means that by merely typing

                     $ task
                     [task project:foo list]

                     ID Project Pri Description
                      1 foo     H   Design foo
                      2 foo         Build foo

   RREEPPOORRTTSS
       The  reports  can  be customized by using the following configuration variables.  The output columns, their labels and the sort order can be set using the corresponding variables
       for each report. Each report name is used as a "command" name. For example

       ttaasskk oovveerrdduuee

       rreeppoorrtt..XX..ddeessccrriippttiioonn
              The description for report X when running the "task help" command.

       rreeppoorrtt..XX..ccoolluummnnss
              This is a comma-separated list of columns and formatting specifiers. See the command 'task columns' for a full list of options and examples.

       rreeppoorrtt..XX..ccoonntteexxtt
              A boolean value representing whether the given report should respect (apply) the currently active context. See CONTEXT section for details about context.  Defaults to 1.

       rreeppoorrtt..XX..llaabbeellss
              The labels for each column that will be used when generating report X. The labels are a comma separated list.

       rreeppoorrtt..XX..ssoorrtt
              The sort order of the tasks in the generated report X. The sort order is specified by using the column ids post-fixed by a "+" for ascending sort order or a  "-"  for  de‐
              scending sort order. The sort IDs are separated by commas.  For example:

                  report.list.sort=due+,priority-,start.active-,project+

              Additionally, after the "+" or "-", there can be a solidus "/" which indicates that there are breaks after the column values change. For example:

                  report.minimal.sort=project+/,description+

              This sort order now specifies that there is a listing break between each project. A listing break is simply a blank line, which provides a visual grouping.

              A special sort value of "none" indicates that no sorting is required, and tasks will be presented in the order (if any) in which they are selected.

       rreeppoorrtt..XX..ffiilltteerr
              This adds a filter to the report X so that only tasks matching the filter criteria are displayed in the generated report.

              There is a special case for 'report.timesheet.filter', which may be specified even though the 'timesheet' report is not very customizable.

       rreeppoorrtt..XX..ddaatteeffoorrmmaatt
              This  adds  a dateformat to the report X that will be used by the "due date" column. If it is not set then dateformat.report and dateformat will be used in this order. See
              the DDAATTEESS section for details on the sequence placeholders.

       rreeppoorrtt..XX..aannnnoottaattiioonnss
              This adds the possibility to control the output of annotations for a task in a report. Deprecated. Use the ddeessccrriippttiioonn column with a format (e.g.,  ddeessccrriippttiioonn..ccoouunntt)  in‐
              stead.

       Taskwarrior comes with a number of predefined reports, which are:

       nneexxtt   Lists the most important tasks.

       lloonngg   Lists all pending tasks and all data, matching the specified criteria.

       lliisstt   Lists all tasks matching the specified criteria.

       llss     Short listing of all tasks matching the specified criteria.

       mmiinniimmaall
              Minimal listing of all tasks matching the specified criteria.

       nneewweesstt Shows the newest tasks.

       oollddeesstt Shows the oldest tasks.

       oovveerrdduuee
              Lists overdue tasks matching the specified criteria.

       aaccttiivvee Lists active tasks matching the specified criteria.

       ccoommpplleetteedd
              Lists completed tasks matching the specified criteria.

       rreeccuurrrriinngg
              Lists recurring tasks matching the specified criteria.

       wwaaiittiinngg
              Lists all waiting tasks matching the specified criteria.

       aallll    Lists all tasks matching the specified criteria.

       bblloocckkeedd
              Lists all tasks that have dependencies.

   UUSSEERR DDEEFFIINNEEDD AATTTTRRIIBBUUTTEESS
       User  defined attributes (UDAs) are an extension mechanism that allows you to define new attributes for Taskwarrior to store and display. One such example is an 'estimate' attri‐
       bute that could be used to store time estimates associated with a task. This 'estimate' attribute is not built in to Taskwarrior, but with a few simple configuration settings you
       can instruct Taskwarrior to store this item, and provide access to it for custom reports and filters.

       This allows you to augment Taskwarrior to accommodate your workflow, or bend the rules and use Taskwarrior to store and synch data that is not necessarily task-related.

       One  important restriction is that because this is an open system that allows the definition of any new attribute, Taskwarrior cannot understand the meaning of that attribute. So
       while Taskwarrior will faithfully store, modify, report, sort and filter your UDA, it does not understand anything about it. For example if you define  a  UDA  named  'estimate',
       Taskwarrior will not know that this value is weeks, hours, minutes, money, or some other resource count.

       uuddaa..<<nnaammee>>..ttyyppee==ssttrriinngg||nnuummeerriicc||ddaattee||dduurraattiioonn
              Defines a UDA called '<name>', of the specified type.

       uuddaa..<<nnaammee>>..llaabbeell==<<ccoolluummnn hheeaaddiinngg>>
              Provides a default report label for the UDA called '<name>'.

       uuddaa..<<nnaammee>>..vvaalluueess==AA,,BB,,CC
              For type 'string' UDAs only, this provides a comma-separated list of acceptable values. In this example, the '<name>' UDA may only contain values 'A', 'B', or 'C', but may
              also contain no value.

              Note that the order of the value is important, and denotes the sort order from highest ('A') to lowest ('C').

              Note that a blank value is permitted.

       uuddaa..<<nnaammee>>..ddeeffaauulltt==......
              Provides a default value for the UDA called '<name>'.

       EExxaammppllee ''eessttiimmaattee'' UUDDAA
              This example shows an 'estimate' UDA that stores specific values for the size of a task.  Note the blank value after 'trivial'.

              uuddaa..eessttiimmaattee..ttyyppee==ssttrriinngg
              uuddaa..eessttiimmaattee..llaabbeell==SSiizzee EEssttiimmaattee
              uuddaa..eessttiimmaattee..vvaalluueess==hhuuggee,,llaarrggee,,mmeeddiiuumm,,ssmmaallll,,ttrriivviiaall,,

              Note that the value are sorted

                  huge > large > medium > small > trivial > ''

   CCOONNTTEEXXTT
       Context setting is a mechanism which allows the user to set a permanent filter, thus avoiding the need to specify one filter repeatedly. More details on usage can be found in the
       task(1) man page.

       The current context is stored in the .taskrc file, along with definitions for all user provided contexts.

       ccoonntteexxtt==<<nnaammee>>
              Stores the value of the currently active context.

       ccoonntteexxtt..<<nnaammee>>..rreeaadd==<<ffiilltteerr>>
       ccoonntteexxtt..<<nnaammee>>..wwrriittee==<<mmooddiiffiiccaattiioonnss>>
              Stores  the  definition of the read or write context with the name <name>. Read context is the default filter applied when the context is active. The write context are the
              default modifications applied to newly added tasks when the context is active.

       ccoonntteexxtt..<<nnaammee>>..rrcc..<<kkeeyy>>==<<vvaalluuee>>
              The rc type allows to override any configuration parameter for the current context, e.g. if the default command for the context home should be changed to home_report,  the
              following statement could be added:

              context.home.rc.default.command=home_report

   SSYYNNCC
       These configuration settings are used to connect and sync tasks with the task server.

       ttaasskkdd..sseerrvveerr==<<hhoosstt>>::<<ppoorrtt>>
              Specifies the hostname and port of the Taskserver. Hostname may be an IPv4 or IPv6 address, or domain. Port is an integer.

       ttaasskkdd..ccrreeddeennttiiaallss==<<oorrggaanniizzaattiioonn>>//<<uusseerr>>//<<kkeeyy>>
              User identification for the Taskserver, which includes a private key.

       ttaasskkdd..cceerrttiiffiiccaattee==<<ppaatthh>>
              Specifies the path to the client certificate used for identification with the Taskserver.

       ttaasskkdd..kkeeyy==<<ppaatthh>>
              Specifies the path to the client key used for encrypted communication with the Taskserver.

       ttaasskkdd..ccaa==<<ppaatthh>>
              Specifies the path to the CA certificate in the event that your Taskserver is using a self-signed certificate. Optional.

       ttaasskkdd..ttrruusstt==ssttrriicctt||iiggnnoorree hhoossttnnaammee||aallllooww aallll
              This  settings  allows you to override the trust level when server certificates are validated. With "allow all", the server certificate is trusted automatically. With "ig‐
              nore hostname", the server certificate is verified but the hostname is ignored. With "strict", the server certificate is verified.  Default  is  "strict",  which  requires
              full validation.

       ttaasskkdd..cciipphheerrss==NNOORRMMAALL
              Override  of  the  cipher  selection. The set of ciphers used by TLS may be controlled by both server and client. There must be some overlap between client and server sup‐
              ported ciphers, or communication cannot occur.  Default is "NORMAL". See GnuTLS documentation for full details.

